### Why?

I mix this functionality into lodash, because I can not `require` some of my klasses thanks to circular requiring errors in node and thought other people might find this useful aswell.
### What do you mean exactly?

Certainly the native `instanceof` operator is better if it is available. But sometimes it isn't.

My implementation is probably optimizable (I wrote this in [CoffeeScript](https://gist.github.com/maschs/f4b890fd752ab7b68d1e) and compiled it for you), but I think the idea is obvious:

``` js
var lodash = require('lodash');

// Public: The instanceOf() functions tests whether an object has in its
//         prototype chain the prototype property of a constructor with the name
//         'klass'.
//
//         If the user passes a function as klass, instanceOf() uses the native
//         instanceof operator instead.
//
// obj   - The object to test as {Object}.
// klass - The klass name as {String}|{Function}.
//
// Returns: {Boolean}.
var instanceOf = function(obj, klass) {
  if (lodash.isFunction(klass)) {
    return obj instanceof klass;
  }
  obj = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);
  while (obj != null) {
    if (obj.constructor.name === klass) {
      return true;
    }
    obj = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);
  }
  return false;
};

lodash.mixin({
  'instanceOf': instanceOf
}, {
  'chain': false
});

module.exports = lodash;
```

And after that I can do things like 

``` coffee
if not _.instanceOf(@repo, 'PromisedGit') 
  throw new Error('Invalid repo!')
```

instead of other, horrible things.

