There's a case:

``` javascript
function provideArgumentWithDefaults (argument) {
    _.defaults(argument, {
        foo: 'bar',
    });
    return argument;
}
```

If `argument` is undefined (one want to create an object with only the default properties) undefined will be returned without the properties which are supposed to be default.
The solution is off course to initialise the new object like this:

``` javascript
function provideArgumentWithDefaults (argument) {
    argument = argument || {}
    _.defaults(argument, {
        foo: 'bar',
    });
    return argument;
}
```

or like this:

``` javascript
function provideArgumentWithDefaults (argument) {
    _.defaults(argument || {}, {
        foo: 'bar',
    });
    return argument;
}
```

What would be nice is something like:

```
_.defaults(object, [source], [initialObject])
```

then instead of doing it manually one could write:

``` javascript
function provideArgumentWithDefaults (argument) {
    _.defaults(argument, {
        foo: 'bar',
    }, {});
    return argument;
}
```

