In some issues, and also in code, there's are references to solving a defaultsDeep via `_.merge` with a `_.defaults` callbacks: `_.defaultsDeep = _.partialRight(_.merge, _.defaults)`

But the result is quite unexpected:

``` javascript
_.defaultsDeep = _.partialRight(_.merge, _.defaults);
_.defaultsDeep(obj1 = {a:{b:{c:1}}}, obj2 = {a:{b:{d:2}}});
// EXPECTED: {a:{b:{c:1, d:2}}}
// REAL: {a:{b:{c:1}}}
```

since merge will use the "non-undefined" result of the callback and stop going deeper i.e. it will compare obj1.a with obj2.a, _.defaults will answer "keep obj1.a", and merge stops

For the expected to take place, one would need:

``` javascript
_.defaultsDeep = function(a,b) {
  return _.isObject(a) ? _.merge(a, b, _.defaultsDeep) : _.defaults(a, b);
}
```

This "unexpected" behaviour seems to be accounted for in a test "should defer to `callback` when it returns a value other than `undefined`", and I can guess the rationale, but maybe _.merge can benefit from another `goDeep` argument, default `false` ?

Not sure what the correct term is, but I want to wrap a function that takes multiple arguments with a function that takes one argument (an array) and `Function.prototype.apply`'s the wrapped function with that argument.

I want to be able to do something like this:

``` js
function printPerson(name, age) {
  document.body.innerHTML +=
    '<p>' + name + ' is ' + age + ' years old</p>';
}

var people = [
  ['Professor', 163],
  ['Leela', 25],
  ['Bender', 1057],
];

people.forEach(_.deapply(printPerson));
```

HTML:

``` text
Professor is 163 years old
Leela is 25 years old
Bender is 1057 years old
```

But obviously, this fails, as there is no `_.deapply` function.

The implementation is trivial:

``` js
_.deapply = function(func, thisArg) {
  return function(args) {
    return func.apply(thisArg, args);
  };
};
```

But perhaps I am missing some `.bind` / `.apply` trickery that will do this for me with only standard Lo-Dash functions?

