When writing real-time applications, one has to resolve getting the data in the app to be eventually consistent. Not only does one have to merge in data to existing data in the app, one has to also figure out how to fill in new data without overwriting existing data. A use case for this method is the following situation:
1. Open web sockets to start listening for push notifications
2. Once the web socket is open, perform a GET on a resource to get the updated state for a resource. 
3. Once step 2's response is received, combine the response data with existing data that may have been sent over the web socket during the round trip.

In my team's app, we generally treat data sent over web sockets to be a higher priority than data received from REST APIs. As such, if data is received over the web socket, we do NOT want to write over the existing data when step 3 is executed. To account for this, we perform a fill - which merges in new data, but does NOT write over existing data. It would be useful if lodash provided an API to handle this with JSON objects. 

I would imagine that the API would work like so:

```
var destination = { "a": 1 };

_.fill(destination, {"a": 2, "b": 3});
// -> {"a": 1, "b": 3}
```
